  "experiments_summary": "The study developed ChEMBL3D, a dataset of over 250 million molecular conformers for 1.8 million drug-like compounds from ChEMBL v34. The dataset construction involved: (1) generating protomers in neutral and ionized states using OpenEye FixpKa, (2) enumerating stereocenters with OpenEye Flipper, (3) generating initial conformers with OpenEye Omega Classic (up to 200 per molecule), and (4) optimizing all structures using AIMNet2 neural network potentials with CPCM implicit solvent to near-DFT accuracy. Post-processing included topology validation, energy-based filtering, and deduplication based on distance matrix changes. The authors then developed LoQI, a stereochemistry-aware diffusion model based on the Megalodon architecture combining Diffusion Transformer (DiT) layers with equivariant graph neural networks (EGNN). The model uses 25 diffusion steps with weighted cosine noise schedules. A novel stereochemical graph augmentation was introduced: for E/Z stereochemistry, four auxiliary edges connect neighbors of double bonds; for R/S stereocenters, directed cycles encode chirality. The model was trained to predict atomic coordinates from noised inputs. Evaluation was performed on: (1) a hold-out set of 37,075 ChEMBL molecules, (2) ChEMBL3D-XL subset with molecules having up to 25 rotatable bonds (300 molecules per rotatable bond count, 100 conformers generated per molecule), (3) Platinum Diverse dataset of 2,879 crystal structures, and (4) six macrocycles from MPCONF196 benchmark and taxol. Performance metrics included relative energy to dataset minimum, optimization convergence, topology preservation, relaxation energy, stereochemistry accuracy (R/S and E/Z), and RMSD to reference structures. DFT validation was performed on 88 examples where LoQI found lower-energy conformers than the dataset reference."
